ve in its approach, In Praise of Nonsense focuses on theories of disappearance, irony, and nonsense, where the pleasures of the imaginary give rise to artistic inspiration. When truth is unhinged, so is falsity, and all artistic thinking is called into question. Ted Hiebert takes on the ambitious project of holding postmodernism accountable for its own conclusions while also considering how those conclusions might still be given philosophical and artistic form.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAesthetics. 0aCreation (Literary, artistic, etc.) 0aCreation (Literary, artistic, etc.). 0aImagination. 0aPostmodernism. 0aUncertainty. 7aART / History / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077358733540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773587335423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773587335/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles